article.headline: Duncan, Nesterovic post double-doubles
article.linkText: San Antonio rolls to seventh win in a row
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The Memphis Grizzlies certainly had their chances. Memphis shot just 5-for-21 in the fourth quarter and went scoreless over the game's final 6:02 in losing 78-67 to the San Antonio Spurs on Monday night. The Grizzlies missed their final eight shots and turned the ball over four times in the final six minutes on their way to a season-low point total. "We had the opportunities because they weren't scoring either," Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. "We had five turnovers and go 1-for-5 on the break. That's 10 times we're down there and nothing's happening. It's frustrating for a young team like we are." Tim Duncan had 21 points and 13 rebounds for his league-leading 20th double-double for the Spurs, who won their seventh straight. Tony Parker added 18 points for San Antonio, which has held its last six opponents to 82 points or less. Rasho Nesterovic added 10 and tied a career-high with 15 rebounds. "Memphis has been winning and they played well," Parker said. "They have one of the best offenses in the league. It was a good test for our defense. Holding them to 67 points was pretty good." Lorenzen Wright scored six points during an 8-0 spurt that brought the Grizzlies within 72-67 with 6:02 left but Memphis wouldn't score again. Bonzi Wells led Memphis with 12 points, but had a breakaway layup blocked by Bruce Bowen to prolong the Grizzlies' drought. James Posey, Pau Gasol and Stromile Swift each had 10. "They got the key rebounds and steals at the end," Wright said. "We did a good job of battling back. In the timeouts, Coach was telling us to keep our cool and not let the lead get too big." Swift scored at the buzzer to end the third to pull Memphis within 63-57 but the Spurs scored the first six points of the fourth to open up a 13-point lead. The Spurs won despite turning the ball over 21 times, including 17 times in the second half. Parker had 12 points in the second quarter to help the Spurs stay in the game despite making just three field goals in a span of 8:57 over the first and second quarters. The Grizzles matched their biggest lead at 36-32 when Parker sparked a comeback by San Antonio with a four-point play, a 3-pointer and baseline jumper with 2.7 seconds left in the first half that gave San Antonio a 43-40 lead.

Game notes
Spurs forward Malik Rose missed his seventh straight game with a strained right calf. ... Grizzlies guard Jason Williams missed his eighth consecutive game with a strained back. ... San Antonio, which took three of four games from Memphis last season, evened the season series at 1-1 this season. The Grizzlies beat the Spurs 88-80, in game in which Duncan sprained his ankle in the first quarter.
